---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import CTABlock from '../../components/CTABlock.astro';
import { business, BASE } from '../../data/business';
import { postBySlug, postsBySlugs, RELATED_POSTS } from '../../data/posts';
import RelatedPosts from '../../components/RelatedPosts.astro';

const post = postBySlug('gutter-cleaning-ayr-kilmarnock-spring')!;
const relatedPosts = postsBySlugs(RELATED_POSTS[post.slug] ?? []).slice(0, 3);
const siteUrl = business.siteUrl.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = `${siteUrl}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = `${siteUrl}${post.ogImage}`;

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  '@id': `${url}#article`,
  headline: post.title,
  description: post.description,
  inLanguage: 'en-GB',
  datePublished: post.date,
  dateModified: post.date,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: post.author,
    worksFor: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  },
  publisher: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  image: [ogImage],
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  articleSection: 'Gutter cleaning',
  keywords: [post.keyword, 'gutter cleaning kilmarnock', 'gutter vacuum ayrshire', 'spring gutter clean', 'blocked gutters ayr'],
  wordCount: post.wordCount,
  about: [{ '@type': 'Place', name: 'Ayr, Scotland' }, { '@type': 'Place', name: 'Kilmarnock, Scotland' }],
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Sorn Handyman Services`}
  description={post.description}
  canonicalPath={`/blog/${post.slug}/`}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  ogType="article"
  extraSchema={articleSchema}
>
  <Breadcrumbs trail={[
    { name: 'Home', href: `${BASE}/` },
    { name: 'Blog', href: `${BASE}/blog/` },
    { name: post.title },
  ]} />

  <article class="container-x py-10 lg:py-14 max-w-3xl">
    <header>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-amber-600">
        <span>{post.area}</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <span class="text-navy-900/60">{post.readMinutes} min read</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <time datetime={post.date} class="text-navy-900/60">{post.dateDisplay}</time>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-navy-900 leading-tight">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-navy-900/75">
        Everybody books gutter cleaning in October. They shouldn't — they should
        book it now. Here's why April is the right month across Ayr, Kilmarnock
        and the rest of East Ayrshire, and what a proper clean actually looks
        like from the ground.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose-sorn mt-8 text-lg cv-auto">
      <p>
        I spend more weeks of the year up gutters than I'd like to admit. After
        doing this in the rain, the dark and the middle of February, I can tell
        you one thing with confidence: the folk who book their
        <a href={`${BASE}/services/gutter-cleaning/`}>gutter clean in April</a>
        have half the problems of the folk who leave it until the leaves are
        already down.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the short version of why spring is the right window for Ayr,
        Kilmarnock and everywhere in between — and what we actually do when we
        turn up with a vac pole on the lawn.
      </p>

      <h2>Why spring beats autumn (every time)</h2>
      <p>
        The instinct is to clean gutters after the trees drop. Makes sense on
        paper. In practice it's the wrong call for three reasons.
      </p>

      <h3>1. Winter has already done its damage</h3>
      <p>
        If your gutters were blocked through Ayrshire's wet season — roughly
        November to March — water has been backing up behind that dam of
        leaves and moss for four months. It's been soaking into your fascia,
        dribbling down the wall behind the downpipe, and freezing expansion-cracks
        into your joints. By April you can <em>see</em> that damage. By October
        it's hidden behind a fresh summer's growth.
      </p>
      <p>
        We find most fascia rot, hopper cracks and loose downpipe brackets on
        spring jobs. Fixing them in April costs a fraction of finding them in
        October when they've had another six months to worsen.
      </p>

      <h3>2. The moss is softer and lighter</h3>
      <p>
        Ayrshire roofs grow moss like a permanent feature. Through the summer
        it dries, hardens and welds itself to your tile joints. In spring it's
        still damp from winter — it comes out of the gutter run with about half
        the effort. We get the job done quicker and you pay less.
      </p>

      <h3>3. You get the summer for the proper fixes</h3>
      <p>
        If a spring clean flags a sagging run, a leaking joint or a broken
        bracket, there's a full dry season ahead to
        <a href={`${BASE}/services/guttering/`}>replace or repair</a> properly.
        Leaving it to autumn means you're chasing a fix in November weather
        with the next storm a week away.
      </p>

      <h2>What we actually do on a gutter clean</h2>
      <p>
        No ladders on your lawn, no boot marks on the roof, no mess on the
        driveway. We use a gutter-vacuum pole system — a long carbon-fibre
        pole with a camera on the end and a high-suction vac at the base. I
        stand on the ground, run the pole up, look down the gutter on a screen,
        and hoover out every run.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>All gutters, hoppers and outlets vac-cleared</li>
        <li>Downpipes flushed with water to confirm flow</li>
        <li>Photo of every cleaned run, sent by WhatsApp before we leave</li>
        <li>Moss and debris bagged and taken away — we pay the tip fee</li>
        <li>Bracket and joint check while the pole's up there</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        That last point matters more than folk realise. Half the time we clear
        a blocked gutter and <em>then</em> find the joint's been leaking
        quietly for a year. We photograph it, quote a repair, and you decide
        whether to book it in. No pressure, no upsell — we'd rather leave you
        with information than a surprise invoice.
      </p>

      <h2>The warning signs you shouldn't leave till June</h2>
      <p>
        Before you book, walk outside and look up. If you see any of these,
        ring us this week:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>A gutter that's sagging visibly</strong> — the bracket is failing or the fascia behind it is soft.</li>
        <li><strong>Water staining on your wall</strong> under a joint or hopper — that joint has been leaking a while.</li>
        <li><strong>Plants growing out of the gutter</strong> — silt has built up deep enough to seed. That gutter is probably 50% full.</li>
        <li><strong>Water overshooting the front of the gutter</strong> in heavy rain — the run is blocked or the gutter has dropped out of level.</li>
        <li><strong>Damp inside an upstairs corner of the house</strong> — classic sign that a gutter is backing up and soaking the wall-top through the eaves.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If you see any of those, book the clean and a repair quote together.
        We do both in the one visit where we can.
      </p>

      <h2>Ayr vs. Kilmarnock — any difference?</h2>
      <p>
        Honest answer: a bit.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/ayr/`}>Ayr</a> properties, especially the
        seafront and Esplanade terraces, get hit with salt-laden air all year.
        Gutter metalwork and paint suffer, and the runs at the front of the
        house silt up with fine sand as well as leaves. We often recommend
        deep-flow replacement gutters on those streets rather than standard
        half-round, because the volume of water coming off big slate roofs
        overwhelms the shallower profile in a proper downpour.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/kilmarnock/`}>Kilmarnock's</a> older tenement
        stock around the town centre has back-court gutters that nobody looks
        at for years at a time. Those are our bread-and-butter spring jobs —
        big cast-iron runs that haven't been touched since the building was
        modernised, usually full of sixty years of silt and one ball a child
        threw up there in 1987.
      </p>

      <h2>What it costs</h2>
      <p>
        Our standard gutter clean starts at
        <strong>£60 for a small terrace</strong> and runs up to about
        <strong>£120 for a big detached</strong> with a complex run. We quote
        honest from a photo — send us a WhatsApp of your house front and back
        and we'll give you a firm number inside an hour.
      </p>
      <p>
        No call-out fee in <a href={`${BASE}/areas/ayr/`}>Ayr</a>,
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/kilmarnock/`}>Kilmarnock</a>,
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/troon/`}>Troon</a>, or anywhere in
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/`}>our East Ayrshire patch</a>. We show up,
        clean, photograph, tidy, and you pay by card or bank transfer.
      </p>
      <p>
        Book now, not in October. Your fascias will thank you.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-navy-900/10 bg-navy-50/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-navy-900/60">Written by</p>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">{post.author}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-900/75 text-sm">{post.authorBio}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <RelatedPosts posts={relatedPosts} eyebrow="Keep reading" heading="Related posts" variant="tinted" />

  <CTABlock
    heading="Ready for a spring gutter clean in Ayr or Kilmarnock?"
    sub="Send a photo of your house to WhatsApp — we'll quote in an hour and book you in this week."
  />
</BaseLayout>
